WEBVTT

00:11.929 --> 00:14.306
Hi, my name is Armond Collins,

00:14.306 --> 00:19.144
and I'm committed
to the University of Southern California.

00:41.542 --> 00:46.380
I'm Tyriq Williams, and I'm taking
my talents to the University of Virginia.

01:07.484 --> 01:12.948
My name is Ramel Evans,

01:12.948 --> 01:18.495
and I'm going to be playing for the CBA...

01:20.622 --> 01:23.417
in China.

01:52.321 --> 01:54.531
Hey, what's up? My name is Deandre Wright.

01:55.365 --> 01:58.952
I may go to the University of Texas
or Georgetown.

01:59.703 --> 02:00.746
Or Indiana State.

02:01.496 --> 02:02.539
I'll let y'all know.

02:04.333 --> 02:05.584
Do you all know who I am?

02:06.335 --> 02:07.461
Do you all know who I am?

02:07.461 --> 02:10.214
Get off of me, man, please!

02:10.214 --> 02:11.507
This ain't right.

02:13.008 --> 02:14.134
Get off of me!

02:14.134 --> 02:15.385
Let me go!

02:17.971 --> 02:21.475
Let me go. Let me go, man.

04:24.097 --> 04:26.141
Crys, you good?

04:28.685 --> 04:30.479
I don't even know what that means anymore.

04:33.649 --> 04:34.691
I feel you.

04:39.154 --> 04:44.451
Last night, Phil, Drew and Musa
made an announcement.

04:46.578 --> 04:47.663
I heard.

04:48.413 --> 04:49.414
They're my henchmen.

04:51.458 --> 04:53.210
You know, y'all are so stupid, right?

04:54.211 --> 04:56.588
I wouldn't say that,
but we definitely not smart.

05:01.844 --> 05:03.637
Your post on IG made you famous.

05:04.555 --> 05:06.265
A million views for calling people out.

05:06.265 --> 05:11.144
Everyone acts
like what happened to me is a joke.

05:13.438 --> 05:14.815
It isn't.

05:15.858 --> 05:16.942
Never was.

05:22.948 --> 05:25.367
We got this community service game today.

05:25.951 --> 05:30.205
Something set up through Coach Ike
and Meg's Swagger DMV program.

05:31.081 --> 05:34.710
School doesn't have their hands on it,
so I can play.

05:36.044 --> 05:38.672
If we all don't end up suspended
from Cedar Cove basketball,

05:38.672 --> 05:41.049
today could be
our last time hooping together.

05:41.633 --> 05:43.177
What about the legal stuff?

05:44.428 --> 05:47.222
My mother's spearheading
a letter campaign to the DA.

05:48.140 --> 05:50.517
Gladiator Sneakers got us
a really dope lawyer.

05:51.435 --> 05:54.479
And I'm trying not to be tight
about all of it.

05:54.479 --> 05:56.023
That's good, Jace.

06:00.527 --> 06:01.528
I gotta go.

06:06.491 --> 06:10.329
Speaking of being famous,
saw your sex tape online.

06:11.705 --> 06:12.706
Kissing video?

06:13.916 --> 06:16.084
Anyway, that's old news.

06:16.627 --> 06:18.337
What? She broke your heart or something?

06:19.338 --> 06:23.258
Believe me, if I want my heart broken,
I know exactly where to go.

06:24.551 --> 06:25.761
What's that supposed to mean?

06:28.514 --> 06:30.098
Excuse me?

06:30.766 --> 06:34.019
After sophomore year, you were the one
who said you needed space.

06:34.019 --> 06:36.355
I said that because you said
you needed time

06:36.355 --> 06:38.524
to focus on taking your game
to the next level.

06:44.571 --> 06:49.576
But I'm glad things
are going so amazingly well with--

06:49.576 --> 06:51.286
- Roderick.
- Right.

06:52.955 --> 06:54.164
Yeah. It's been a little hectic.

06:54.164 --> 06:58.043
So him and I decided to take a break.

07:04.925 --> 07:08.804
There has been a lot of heat on us.

07:10.305 --> 07:11.598
Not everyone can handle it.

07:15.853 --> 07:16.854
Ball out, okay?

07:18.188 --> 07:19.189
Always.

07:43.213 --> 07:44.756
- Morning, Coach Meg.
- Morning.

07:45.257 --> 07:46.758
- Coach Ike.
- Morning, Mus.

07:47.509 --> 07:49.303
Hop on the bus. First come, first serve.

07:55.309 --> 07:56.310
Thank you.

08:05.110 --> 08:06.528
<i>Your dad and I talked about it.</i>

08:06.528 --> 08:08.822
We don't feel good about you going.

08:09.573 --> 08:11.450
It doesn't matter
if the school sanctioned it.

08:12.743 --> 08:13.744
This is my team.

08:14.286 --> 08:16.747
And if there's any time
to stand with them, it's now.

08:16.747 --> 08:18.749
They're playing
an exhibition game at a prison.

08:19.499 --> 08:21.835
And by the end of the week,
some of them might end up there.

08:21.835 --> 08:24.922
- It's a detention center.
- It is a sinking ship.

08:33.054 --> 08:34.181
The answer is no.

08:35.599 --> 08:36.808
Bus is leaving in ten.

08:36.808 --> 08:38.477
We've talked about this.

08:38.477 --> 08:39.686
And it doesn't make sense.

08:40.270 --> 08:42.438
I'm not comfortable
with that group of individuals.

08:42.438 --> 08:45.734
- That group of individuals are my friends.
- I'm not comfortable with that either.

08:45.734 --> 08:47.110
And that's your problem.

08:48.612 --> 08:49.988
I'm going to play.

08:50.989 --> 08:52.908
I did not sign that consent form,

08:53.492 --> 08:54.326
and I don't intend to.

08:55.953 --> 08:57.246
This is bullshit.

08:59.957 --> 09:02.292
How are we even able
to afford an attorney, Ma?

09:02.292 --> 09:03.418
We can't.

09:04.127 --> 09:07.589
But Alonzo from Gladiator Sneakers,
he's taking care of it.

09:07.589 --> 09:10.801
He just asked us to keep it quiet.

09:17.766 --> 09:18.725
Hey, Ma.

09:19.768 --> 09:21.228
It's all gonna be okay.

09:24.982 --> 09:26.650
Yeah, it is.

09:39.955 --> 09:41.748
I agree with your decision to stay home.

09:41.748 --> 09:45.586
Nicholas, sometimes you have to do
what's best for the team.

09:47.296 --> 09:49.423
But sometimes you have to do
what's best for you.

10:06.231 --> 10:07.316
What's up, homey?

10:20.329 --> 10:23.081
The other players either canceled
or didn't respond to my text.

10:28.837 --> 10:30.297
Our starting five is on the bus.

10:35.135 --> 10:36.470
I know we said we'd be there.

10:37.262 --> 10:41.308
I'm just triple-checking
that we feel all right about this timing.

10:41.892 --> 10:42.809
I think it's necessary.

10:44.728 --> 10:45.729
I don't know what to think.

10:49.149 --> 10:52.819
Maybe it's something the kids need.

10:54.279 --> 10:57.866
With all due respect,
I know what my kid needs.

11:00.869 --> 11:01.787
Let's do this.

11:02.287 --> 11:03.288
Okay.

11:13.215 --> 11:14.216
Hey, hold on.

11:27.437 --> 11:28.689
What's up, Coach?

11:33.610 --> 11:34.736
What's up, Royale?

11:41.159 --> 11:42.035
Okay.

11:49.710 --> 11:53.005
Our athletic director is not exactly
my biggest fan.

11:53.005 --> 11:54.047
Need a tissue?

11:55.090 --> 11:57.843
Not shedding tears, but he may fire me.

11:57.843 --> 11:59.803
Can't say I'd miss working with him,

11:59.803 --> 12:02.681
but I would miss that big-ass house
he got me and Tonya.

12:04.766 --> 12:06.018
Me too.

13:04.368 --> 13:05.786
We appreciate y'all visiting.

13:06.495 --> 13:09.456
Just got to let Betty do her job here. Search.

13:10.916 --> 13:12.668
Let's go. Search.

13:17.047 --> 13:18.006
Go on.

13:36.233 --> 13:39.945
- Wait a second, I know you.
- Hey.

13:40.445 --> 13:43.448
- I'm Phil Marksby, Mr. Carlos.
- Nice to know you, Mr. Phil.

13:43.448 --> 13:44.658
- Pleasure to meet you.
- All right.

13:44.658 --> 13:47.286
- Hello, Mr. Carlos. I'm Jace Carson.
- How you doing, brother?

13:47.286 --> 13:48.787
- Good.
- What's up, man?

13:48.787 --> 13:49.913
What's going on there, Ikey?

13:50.497 --> 13:52.624
Man, I ain't seen you since
you was knee-high to a grasshopper.

13:53.917 --> 13:55.127
Man, how's the family doing?

13:55.127 --> 13:57.087
- Everybody's good, sir. Everybody's good.
- Fantastic.

13:57.087 --> 14:00.465
Everybody, this is John Carlos, okay?

14:00.465 --> 14:02.968
- Yeah.
- He was in the 1968 Olympics.

14:03.552 --> 14:07.514
Now, I want y'all to go ahead,
take a look at this.

14:10.434 --> 14:14.313
This man is a hero to many of us.

14:14.980 --> 14:18.108
Left fist in the air
during the national anthem.

14:18.108 --> 14:20.194
He loved his country enough
to challenge it.

14:21.695 --> 14:23.572
Okay,
so go ahead and introduce yourselves.

14:24.072 --> 14:26.867
- Dr. Carlos, Naim Rahaim.
- All right, brother? All right.

14:26.867 --> 14:28.702
- Musa Rahaim. It's an honor, sir.
- Yeah.

14:28.702 --> 14:30.579
- Drew Murphy, sir.
- All right, brother.

14:30.579 --> 14:32.581
- Royale Hughes.
- Nice to know you, brother.

14:32.581 --> 14:34.625
- Nick Mendez. Thank you for everything.
- All right, Nick.

14:34.625 --> 14:36.335
- Megan Bailey.
- Thank you, Coach.

14:36.919 --> 14:40.088
All right. Now,
I'd like to pose a question to you guys.

14:40.088 --> 14:44.218
What is the largest mental health
provider in the United States?

14:47.304 --> 14:48.222
Yes, sir, Phil.

14:48.222 --> 14:50.265
- Prisons.
- Absolutely correct.

14:50.265 --> 14:54.394
There's prisons. There's jails.
And there's detention centers.

14:54.394 --> 14:59.191
In this country, the majority of people
with mental illness are behind bars.

14:59.191 --> 15:04.446
We also incarcerate more people per capita
than any other country in the world.

15:04.446 --> 15:05.864
And at this day and time,

15:06.365 --> 15:10.577
there are more Black people
in the penitentiaries across this nation

15:10.577 --> 15:14.915
than there were Black people enslaved
before the Civil War.

15:15.415 --> 15:19.837
The prison system
has become the new plantation.

15:19.837 --> 15:21.547
Does that sound like a problem?

15:21.547 --> 15:22.881
- Yeah.
- Absolutely, sir.

15:22.881 --> 15:24.550
Now, these young men out there

15:24.550 --> 15:26.552
that you guys
are going to play against today,

15:26.552 --> 15:30.264
it's been buzzing around about--
They out here to kick y'all ass.

15:32.808 --> 15:34.893
So in turn, I want you guys to think

15:34.893 --> 15:38.981
about the same premise
of kicking their asses.

15:39.690 --> 15:40.524
All right?

15:40.524 --> 15:43.777
All right, guys, I want you to remember
this when you go into the game today:

15:43.777 --> 15:45.362
Winners are made on the court.

15:46.530 --> 15:48.740
Champions are made off the court.

15:49.658 --> 15:51.034
- Thank you.
- Yes, sir.

15:51.535 --> 15:54.621
Now we're going to turn the program
over to Sergeant Hampton.

15:54.621 --> 15:56.206
- Hello.
- Hello. Hi.

15:56.707 --> 16:00.294
The Maryland Youth Facility
houses male incarcerated people

16:00.294 --> 16:02.379
from the ages of 13 to 17.

16:02.379 --> 16:06.049
None of the people you'll interact with
today will have weapons of any kind,

16:06.049 --> 16:08.135
and you will only be interacting
with the young men

16:08.135 --> 16:09.928
who have exhibited good behavior.

16:09.928 --> 16:13.515
I'm gonna split you off into groups
and let you visit various classrooms.

16:14.016 --> 16:15.017
As Mr. Carlos mentioned,

16:15.017 --> 16:17.603
we want our young men
to have college in their future,

16:17.603 --> 16:20.981
so you are encouraged to engage.

16:22.149 --> 16:23.525
- All right?
- All right.

16:23.525 --> 16:25.402
- Thank you.
- Let's get you all processed.

16:28.822 --> 16:29.948
Thank you.

16:29.948 --> 16:33.118
Phil Marksby, Musa Rahaim,
Drew Murphy, and not to mention,

16:33.118 --> 16:35.329
Jace Carson, got on the biggest stage
they could find

16:35.329 --> 16:38.081
and in one swoop embarrassed Cedar Cove.

16:39.124 --> 16:42.419
Four of our starters
could end up in jail or on probation.

16:42.419 --> 16:45.839
And you, my friend,
bear much of the responsibility.

16:46.548 --> 16:47.758
How am I involved?

16:48.884 --> 16:51.303
You convinced the board
for me to hire Ike as head coach.

16:51.303 --> 16:52.679
Were he a better role model,

16:53.180 --> 16:55.724
this whole thing
could have been contained.

16:55.724 --> 16:56.892
So it's safe to assume

16:56.892 --> 16:59.603
that you're considering
the pros and cons of expulsion.

17:00.646 --> 17:02.439
This institution is bigger than the kids.

17:02.439 --> 17:04.107
Nothing is bigger than the kids.

17:04.107 --> 17:07.486
This institution is bigger
than those four kids.

17:08.569 --> 17:10.656
I assume, like us,
you have others to save.

17:18.704 --> 17:21.415
The governing board of
the Maryland Unified Athletic Council

17:21.415 --> 17:23.126
should take the lead on this.

17:23.126 --> 17:25.753
Look, you and me both know
how restrictive they are.

17:25.753 --> 17:28.590
How buttoned up
they want their athletes to be.

17:29.174 --> 17:33.679
If Cedar Cove expels the Cedar Cove Four,
as they're being called,

17:33.679 --> 17:36.348
or if Gladiator pulls their sponsorship,

17:37.432 --> 17:39.977
that's bad PR for the both of us. But--

17:39.977 --> 17:42.855
You're proposing
we let the MUA be the bad guys.

17:44.731 --> 17:48.110
They analyze the series of events,
make a ruling concerning their future play

17:49.736 --> 17:50.696
and we follow suit?

17:50.696 --> 17:54.032
I think following their
conservative recommendations

17:54.032 --> 17:55.200
may be a better way to lead.

17:58.120 --> 18:00.539
I thought your sympathies lay
with the Swagger players.

18:01.290 --> 18:03.667
They do, 100%.

18:06.211 --> 18:09.423
But as you said,
there are others to save, right?

18:57.930 --> 19:00.390
"What happens to a dream deferred?

19:01.141 --> 19:04.603
Does it dry up like a raisin in the sun?

19:05.604 --> 19:08.815
Or fester like a sore-- And then run?

19:10.275 --> 19:12.402
Does it stink like rotten meat?

19:13.320 --> 19:17.449
Or crust and sugar over--
like a syrupy sweet?

19:19.076 --> 19:21.662
Maybe it just sags like a heavy load.

19:23.205 --> 19:24.748
Or does it explode?"

19:26.667 --> 19:29.211
What do you think Langston Hughes
is trying to say with that poem?

19:29.837 --> 19:34.216
If people don't get opportunities
or figure their lives out,

19:34.216 --> 19:35.342
their dreams can go away.

19:35.926 --> 19:39.888
And when your dreams go away,
shit can get crazy for you.

19:39.888 --> 19:41.056
You're already crazy.

19:41.557 --> 19:42.724
Settle down.

19:45.686 --> 19:46.728
Thank you.

19:47.646 --> 19:50.774
I noticed one of our visitors
is pretty adept with Langston Hughes.

19:50.774 --> 19:51.859
Am I right?

19:54.736 --> 19:56.655
Sorry. Yes.

19:57.781 --> 20:00.367
My mother used to read his poems to me

20:01.368 --> 20:05.914
when she was locked up.

20:05.914 --> 20:08.667
If you don't mind me asking,
how long was she incarcerated?

20:09.793 --> 20:10.627
Two years.

20:12.713 --> 20:15.799
Do you remember any lines
from one of the poems?

20:15.799 --> 20:18.010
- I think I might.
- We'd love to hear it.

20:18.552 --> 20:19.803
Come join us.

20:35.611 --> 20:39.281
"Well, son, I'll tell you:

20:41.742 --> 20:44.870
Life for me ain't been no crystal stair.

20:47.623 --> 20:48.707
It's had tacks in it...

20:51.835 --> 20:52.961
and splinters,

20:54.129 --> 20:55.339
and boards torn up,

20:56.173 --> 20:58.050
places with no carpet on the floor.

20:58.926 --> 20:59.927
But all the time

21:01.428 --> 21:02.679
I'se been a-climbin' on

21:04.348 --> 21:05.682
and reachin' landin's...

21:07.851 --> 21:09.394
and turnin' corners,

21:10.187 --> 21:13.857
and sometimes goin' in the dark

21:15.317 --> 21:16.985
where there ain't been no light."

21:27.621 --> 21:31.542
"So boy, don't you turn back.

21:32.876 --> 21:34.795
Don't you set down on those steps

21:34.795 --> 21:35.963
'cause it's kinda hard.

21:35.963 --> 21:37.339
Don't you fall now...

21:40.384 --> 21:41.885
for I'se still goin', honey.

21:42.970 --> 21:44.263
I'se still climbin',

21:44.263 --> 21:49.142
and for me,
life ain't been no crystal stair."

22:01.113 --> 22:03.198
Well done. Thank you.

22:24.094 --> 22:25.679
Our students are future scientists.

22:25.679 --> 22:29.141
They'll be gardening,
working with solar power,

22:29.141 --> 22:31.143
and this semester, they're working
with bee colonies

22:31.143 --> 22:32.853
and understanding how bees help the earth.

22:32.853 --> 22:34.313
That's amazing.

22:34.313 --> 22:36.815
The biggest de-escalator to violence
in this detention center

22:36.815 --> 22:38.483
has been the classes we've offered.

22:50.954 --> 22:52.831
Is it all right? He played for me.

22:59.254 --> 23:02.090
- How you doing, Coach?
- It's good to see you, Vince.

23:02.674 --> 23:05.761
- What up, Drew? Boy.
- Real good to see you, Vince.

23:08.222 --> 23:09.223
Hey.

23:11.767 --> 23:12.851
I tried reaching you.

23:15.395 --> 23:19.483
Look, I'm sorry. I know.

23:21.985 --> 23:25.364
That is why you must challenge
each claim and not each person.

23:28.158 --> 23:31.286
Class, we have some visitors today
from Cedar Cove Prep.

23:31.286 --> 23:32.412
Let's welcome them.

23:34.289 --> 23:35.457
Hey.

23:36.708 --> 23:39.962
So, which one of you is the star
on the debate team?

23:40.546 --> 23:43.173
- Star?
- That would be Royale.

23:44.550 --> 23:48.011
This is a rare treat for us.
You see, this is our debate class,

23:48.011 --> 23:50.848
and we never get the opportunity
to debate with someone of your stature.

23:51.515 --> 23:54.059
Hold on.
I think there is some kind of confusion.

23:54.059 --> 23:56.812
I just joined the debate team
this semester and I'm an alternate,

23:56.812 --> 23:58.564
but somebody quit.
So now I'm first speaker.

23:58.564 --> 24:01.108
- But I don't think it's--
- Even an alternate at Cedar Cove is elite.

24:02.025 --> 24:05.028
It really would be a rare treat for you
to debate one of our students.

24:05.529 --> 24:06.613
What do you say, Cedar Cove?

24:07.614 --> 24:10.909
- Ce--
- I don't think he's exactly asking.

24:13.871 --> 24:14.705
Yeah.

24:40.397 --> 24:43.567
All right.
You've been given your prep notes.

24:43.567 --> 24:45.319
The debate topic is:

24:45.819 --> 24:50.699
America's Independence Day
should be January 1st, 1863,

24:50.699 --> 24:53.577
the date that
the Emancipation Proclamation was signed.

24:53.577 --> 24:56.246
Royale Hughes has opted
for the affirmative.

24:56.830 --> 24:59.124
Royale, the floor is yours.

25:04.171 --> 25:10.010
Resolved. America's Independence Day
should be January 1st, 1863,

25:10.010 --> 25:12.221
when the Emancipation Proclamation
was signed.

25:12.221 --> 25:14.014
According to the Library of Congress,

25:14.014 --> 25:18.018
on July 4th, 1776,
the Declaration of Independence announced

25:18.018 --> 25:19.811
the colonies' separation
from Great Britain.

25:19.811 --> 25:23.190
The decree was,
"All men are created equal."

25:24.274 --> 25:29.279
However, all men and women did not have
the legal right to be treated equally.

25:31.114 --> 25:34.493
According to the National Archives,
on January 1st, 1863,

25:35.452 --> 25:37.788
the Emancipation Proclamation
was announced.

25:38.455 --> 25:42.459
Thousands of enslaved people attained
their freedom in an unjust society

25:42.459 --> 25:44.127
where we were told we were barely human.

25:44.127 --> 25:46.380
African Americans
walked off the plantations

25:46.380 --> 25:49.550
and walked away from their "slave owners."

25:49.550 --> 25:53.053
The Pittsburgh Courier reports
that we were legally emancipated.

25:54.304 --> 25:57.808
But we were still mistreated,
denied our rights.

25:58.559 --> 26:01.395
In fact, we were denied
the information of our own freedom.

26:04.189 --> 26:10.279
However, we do not mark this date
because emancipation was finally realized.

26:11.029 --> 26:14.324
We mark this date because emancipation
was finally proclaimed.

26:16.368 --> 26:17.202
Thank you.

26:21.164 --> 26:22.165
Marcus Johnson.

26:33.051 --> 26:36.138
When I get released next month,
it'll be bittersweet.

26:37.431 --> 26:41.935
I mean, let's face it, I won't have to sit
next to Gary and deal with his bad breath.

26:49.443 --> 26:53.197
But my brother is in this institution.

26:55.199 --> 26:58.994
Like, literally, my biological brother
is sitting right there.

27:01.455 --> 27:03.582
See, I'm being released
due to good behavior.

27:04.416 --> 27:05.375
He isn't.

27:08.545 --> 27:10.881
And when I go home, my mother will hug me.

27:12.090 --> 27:13.842
But there will still be a hole
in her heart

27:14.343 --> 27:16.220
because her other son
never walked through that door.

